CPU Cache Locality (L5 Topic)

          This is one topic that separates senior engineers from average candidates.
          
          Suppose:
          
                  int[] arr = new int[100000];
          
          The CPU loads memory in cache lines (typically 64 bytes on modern processors).
          
          Since array elements are stored together, when one cache line is loaded, several adjacent integers become available immediately.
          
          When iterating through the array sequentially, the CPU often already has the next values in cache.
          
          This is called:
          
                        Cache Locality

It is one reason arrays perform so well in practice.
